{{Infobox Song Contest |name = Eurovision Young Musicians |year = 1982 |logo = |size = |final = 11 May 1982 |presenters = [[Humphrey Burton]] |exsupervisor = Frank Naef |exproducer = Roy Tipping |conductor = [[Bryden Thomson]] |director = Peter Butler |host = [[British Broadcasting Corporation]] (BBC) |venue = [[Free Trade Hall]], [[Manchester]], [[United Kingdom]] |winmusician = {{ubl|{{Esc|Germany|Musicians}}|[[Markus Pawlik]]}} |vote = Jury chose their top 3 favourites by vote. |entries = 6 |debut = {{ubl|{{Esc|Austria|Musicians}}|{{Esc|France|Musicians}}|{{Esc|Germany|Musicians}}|{{Esc|Norway|Musicians}}|{{Esc|Switzerland|Musicians}}|{{Esc|United Kingdom|Musicians}}}} |return = |withdraw = |null = |interval = Interview with the artists <!-- Map Legend Colours --> | Green = Y | Green SA = | Purple = | Red = | Yellow = }} The '''Eurovision Young Musicians 1982''' was the first edition of the [[Eurovision Young Musicians]], a [[wikt:biennial|biennial]] event inspired by the success of the [[BBC Young Musician of the Year]].<ref name="History"/><ref name=Origins/> The contest took place at the [[Free Trade Hall]] in [[Manchester]], United Kingdom on 11 May 1982, and was organised by the [[European Broadcasting Union]] (EBU) and host broadcaster the [[British Broadcasting Corporation]] (BBC).<ref name=Show>{{cite web|title=Eurovision Young Musicians 1982: About the show|url=http://www.youngmusicians.tv/page/history/by-year/contest?event=1943#About_the_show|website=youngmusicians.tv|publisher=European Broadcasting Union|accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref> Musicians from six participating countries took part in début contest, which was televised across the [[Eurovision (network)|Eurovision Network]]. [[Humphrey Burton]] was the host of the contest and welcomed all of the participants in English, French, and German.<ref name=Show/>
Each of the six participating countries sent either a male or female artist who was no older than 19 years of age, to represent them by playing an [[instrumental]] and a [[Musical ensemble|musical piece]] of their choice, and were accompanied by the [[BBC Northern Symphony Orchestra]], under the [[Conducting|conductor leadership]] of [[Bryden Thomson]].<ref name=Show/> The winner received a cash prize of £1,000.<ref name=Show/>
Germany's Markus Pawlik won the contest, with France and Switzerland placing second and third respectively.<ref name=Results>{{cite web|title=Eurovision Young Musicians 1982 (Participants)|url=http://www.youngmusicians.tv/page/history/by-year/contest?event=1943#Participants|website=youngmusicians.tv|publisher=European Broadcasting Union|accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref> It was also notable that Germany won the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1982]] just a few weeks earlier in [[Harrogate]].<ref name=Eurovision>{{cite web|title=Eurovision Song Contest 1982|url=http://www.eurovision.tv/page/history/by-year/contest/year-page-new?event=298|website=eurovision.tv|publisher=European Broadcasting Union|accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref>
==History== {{Main|Eurovision Young Musicians|BBC Young Musician of the Year}} The Eurovision Young Musicians, inspired by the success of the [[BBC Young Musician of the Year]], is a [[wikt:biennial|biennial]] competition organised by the [[European Broadcasting Union]] (EBU) for European [[musician]]s that are 18 years old or younger.<ref name="History"/><ref name=Origins>{{cite web|last1=Jacob|first1=Jon|title=Past, present and future – The BBC and its Young Musician Competition|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/aboutthebbc/posts/Past-present-and-future-The-BBC-and-its-Young-Musician-Competition|website=bbc.co.uk|publisher=BBC|accessdate=6 October 2014|date=20 May 2013}}</ref> Some participating countries held national heats in order to select their representatives for the contest. The first edition of the Eurovision Young Musicians took place in [[Manchester]], United Kingdom on 11 May 1982 and six countries took part.
The BBC Young Musician of the Year is a televised national music competition. Broadcast originally on [[BBC Two]] biennially, and then on [[BBC Four]] years later.<ref name="History">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/youngmusician/history/|title=History. How it all started|accessdate=6 March 2008|publisher=[[BBC|British Broadcasting Corporation]] (BBC)| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080407221834/http://www.bbc.co.uk/youngmusician/history/| archivedate= 7 April 2008 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> Despite the name, and hosted by the [[BBC|British Broadcasting Corporation]] (BBC), the competition, a former member of [[European Union of Music Competitions for Youth]], is designed for British [[Percussion instrument|percussion]], [[Keyboard instrument|keyboard]], [[String instrument|string]], [[Brass instrument|brass]] and [[woodwind instrument|woodwind]] players, all of whom must be eighteen years of age or under on 1 January in the relevant year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/youngmusician/competition/|title=BBC Young Musician of the Year|accessdate=4 March 2008|publisher=BBC}}</ref>
The competition was established in 1978 by [[Humphrey Burton]] and Walter Todds, both of whom are former members of the BBC Television Music Department.<ref name="History"/> [[Michael Hext]], a trombonist, was the inaugural winner. In 1994, the usage of percussion instruments was first permitted, alongside the existing keyboard, string, brass and woodwind categories.<ref name="History"/> The competition has five stages, which consist of regional auditions, category auditions, category finals, semi-finals and the final.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/youngmusician/entrydetails/stages.shtml|title=Stages of the Competition|accessdate=3 March 2008|publisher=BBC}}</ref>
==Location== {{details|topic=the host venue|Free Trade Hall}} [[File:Manchester Free Trade Hall (Radisson Edwardian Hotel).jpg|150 px|thumb|left|The façade of the Free Trade Hall]] The Free Trade Hall in Peter Street, [[Manchester]], England, was the host venue for the first edition of the Eurovision Young Musicians.<ref name=Show/> The Italian [[Palazzo style architecture|palazzo-style]] hall was built on a [[trapeziform]] site in [[ashlar]] [[sandstone]]. It has a two-storey, nine-bay [[facade]] and concealed roof. On Peter Street, its ground floor [[arcade (architecture)|arcade]] has rectangular [[pier]]s with round-headed arches and [[spandrel]]s bearing the [[Coat of arms|coats of arms]] of Lancashire towns that took part in the [[Anti-Corn Law League|Anti-Corn Law movement]]. The upper floor has a [[colonnade]]d arcade, its [[Tympanum (architecture)|tympana]] [[frieze]] is richly decorated with carved figures representing free trade, the arts, commerce, manufacture and the continents. Above the tympanum is a prominent cornice with [[balustrade]]d [[parapet]]. The upper floor has paired [[Ionic order|Ionic]] [[column]]s to each bay and a tall window with a [[pediment]]ed [[architrave]] behind a [[balustrade]]d [[balcony]]. The return sides have three bays in a matching but simpler style of blank arches. The rear wall was rebuilt in 1950–51 with [[pilaster]]s surmounted by relief figures representing the entertainment which took place in the old hall. The Large Hall was in a classical style with a [[coffer]]ed ceiling, the walls had wood panelling in oak, walnut and sycamore. [[Nikolaus Pevsner|Pevsner]] described it as "the noblest monument in the [[Cinquecento]] style in England", whilst Hartwell considered it "a classic which belongs in the canon of historic English architecture."{{sfnp|Hartwell|2001|p=93|ps=}}
==Format== <!-- [[WP:NFCC]] violation: [[File:Bryden Thomson.jpg|150 px|thumb|right|Bryden Thomson, who conducted the BBC Northern Symphony Orchestra during the 1982 contest]] --> [[Humphrey Burton]] was the host of the inaugural contest, and welcomed representatives from six participating countries in English, French, and German.<ref name=Show/> Each participating country were able to send male or female artists who were no older than 19 years of age, to represent them by playing an instrumental and a musical piece of their choice.<ref name=Show/> They were all accompanied by the [[BBC Northern Symphony Orchestra]], which was conducted by [[Bryden Thomson]].<ref name=Show/> The winner received a cash prize of £1,000.<ref name=Show/>
