{{Infobox recurring event | name = Nobel Banquet | native_name = Nobelfesten | native_name_lang = Swedish | logo = | image = Panoramic Shot Nobel Banquet 2005.jpg | imagesize = 240px | caption = 2005 Nobel Banquet | status = | genre = [[Banquet]] | date = 10 December | frequency = Annual | venue = [[Blue Hall]], [[Stockholm City Hall]] | location = [[Stockholm]], Sweden | coordinates = | country = Sweden | first = {{Start date|1901}} | founder_name = | last = | prev = | next = | participants = | attendance = | area = | budget = | activity = | patron = | organised = | people = | website = }}
The '''Nobel Banquet''' ({{lang-sv|Nobelfesten}}) is an annual banquet held on 10 December in the [[Blue Hall]] of [[Stockholm City Hall]], after the [[Nobel Prize]] [[ceremony]].<ref name="auto">{{cite web|url=http://www.stockholm.se/OmStockholm/Stadshuset/Festlokaler/Nobelfesten/|title=Nobelfesten - Festen|publisher=Stockholm.se|accessdate=17 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/4597253/nobel-prize-banquet-watch-live/|title=Watch the Nobel Prize Banquet Live from Stockholm|website=Time|accessdate=30 November 2018}}</ref> At the banquet, for which a formal dress code exists, a [[Course (food)|multi-course dinner]] is served and entertainment provided.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thelocal.se/20151209/six-things-to-know-about-swedens-poshest-dinner|title=Six things to know about Sweden's poshest dinner|date=9 December 2015|publisher=The Local|accessdate=30 November 2018}}</ref> After the dinner, a dance is held in the [[Golden Hall (Stockholm City Hall)|Golden Hall]].<ref name="auto1">{{cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/nobel-banquet-a-sumptuous-serve-for-laureates-and-royals/a-41708521|title=Nobel Banquet: A sumptuous serve for laureates and royals - DW - 08.12.2017|first=Deutsche Welle|last=(www.dw.com)|website=DW.COM|accessdate=30 November 2018}}</ref> The event is broadcast live on [[SVT]] and [[Sveriges Radio]], and abroad with generally high ratings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royalcourt.se/brollopet/historikochtraditioner/taffeln.4.7eb872b11280345f9fc80001204.html|title=Taffeln|publisher=Royal Court|accessdate=11 October 2014}}</ref>
==History== [[Image:Nobel banquet 1958.jpg|right|thumb|alt=Black-and-white photo of large banquet|1958 Nobel Banquet in Stockholm City Hall's Golden Hall]] The first banquet, for 113 male guests, was held in 1901<ref>[https://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/award_ceremonies/menus/soderlind/ Award ceremonies] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130428151100/http://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/award_ceremonies/menus/soderlind/ |date=April 28, 2013 }}</ref> and until 1923 it was known as the Nobel Dinner ({{lang-sv|Nobelmiddagen}}).<ref name="auto2">{{cite web|url=http://www.stockholm.se/OmStockholm/Stadshuset/Festlokaler/Nobelfesten/|title=Nobelfesten|publisher=|accessdate=11 October 2014}}</ref> Until 1930 the banquet was held in Vinterträdgården at Stockholm's [[Grand Hôtel (Stockholm)|Grand Hôtel Royal]],<ref>Levinovitz, Agneta Wallin, 2011, pagr 127</ref> and it has also been held in the Golden Hall of the [[Swedish Academy]] (Svenska Akademien).<ref name="nobelprize.org">{{cite web|url=https://www.nobelprize.org/ceremonies/the-nobel-prize-award-ceremonies-and-banquets/|title=The Nobel Prize Award Ceremonies and Banquets|publisher=nobelprize.org|accessdate=30 November 2018}}</ref>
The banquet hosts 1,300 guests (including the [[Swedish Royal Family]]) and 200 students. Its host, the chair of the [[Nobel Foundation]], is always seated at the [[Monarchy of Sweden|royal]] table.<ref name="auto1"/>
During the dinner (usually four hours long) each Nobel Prize recipient makes a speech, often lighthearted in character.<ref name="auto2"/> There are two ceremonial cheers: one for the Swedish monarch and the other, made by the monarch, in memory of [[Alfred Nobel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100826112854/http://www.losnummer.se/wp-content/uppladdat/2009/07/7-07.pdf|title=The Nobel Banquet |date=26 August 2010|publisher=|accessdate=29 November 2018}}</ref> The speeches and cheers are presented by the banquet's toastmaster, traditionally a Swedish student who holds the job for four years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ssco.se/nobeltoastmaster/|title=SSCO och Nobelstiftelsen söker ny toastmaster till Nobel|publisher=|accessdate=11 October 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160324141142/http://www.ssco.se/nobeltoastmaster/|archivedate=24 March 2016|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151216154102/http://www.ingenjorskarriar.se/din_utveckling/article3952991.ece|title=Ingenjörens uppdrag: Vara Nobelfestens toastmaster - Ingenjörskarriär|date=16 December 2015|publisher=|accessdate=29 November 2018}}</ref>
Service during the banquet is provided by [[waiting staff]], [[chefs]], and others who are trained for several weeks.<ref name="nobelprize.org"/> Since the 1970s, flowers for the banquet have been provided by the Italian city of [[Sanremo]] (where Nobel lived during his final years).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.svd.se/nyheter/inrikes/forsta-nobelmiddagen-for-sveriges-nye-prins_5801727.svd|title=Första nobelmiddagen för Sveriges nye prins|work=SvD.se|accessdate=11 October 2014}}</ref> They are grown in the [[province of Imperia]] in the [[Liguria]] region of Italy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dn.se/resor/besok-nobels-blommor|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111004211014/http://www.dn.se/resor/besok-nobels-blommor|dead-url=yes|archive-date=4 October 2011|title=Besök Nobels blommor|work=DN.SE|accessdate=11 October 2014|df=}}</ref>
